<table width="640" align="center">
  <tr>
    <td class="style3"> At the end of each period all Shari's Restaurants conduct a full inventory to calculate exact food cost. &nbsp; During weeks one through three of the period, we calculate food cost based on sales and purchases: <br></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style1"><div align="center" class="style2"><span class="style4">Purchases (divided by) sales = food cost</span><br> 
      <br>
    </div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style3">This is not a <strong>“true” </strong> food cost since it is calculated on fluctuating purchases and not on actual food used. &nbsp; On the fourth Wednesday of the period, after inventory, purchases are adjusted to reflect <strong>“true” </strong> food cost based on the actual food that was used that period. &nbsp;&nbsp; </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style1">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style3">Current inventory is compared to the previous inventory and excess food is deducted from purchases giving the manager a credit if he has more food on the shelves then he did a period ago. &nbsp;&nbsp; On the reverse, if the store has less food on hand, the value of the food is added to purchases thereby increasing food cost. &nbsp; Thus, real or actual food cost is calculated by: <br></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style1"><div align="center" class="style2"><span class="style4">Purchases (plus or minus) inventory variance (divided by sales) = true food cost</span><br>
      <br> 
    </div></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style3">As you can see, food used and accurate inventory procedures are what determine food cost. &nbsp; One cannot affect food cost by manipulating (cutting) a Sysco order; once inventory is taken the decrease of food will be evident and will be added to purchases.</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style3">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style3">At Shari's we have very specific rules for counting and extending inventory. &nbsp; Once inventory is taken, the amounts are entered into an inventory program on the computer to calculate its value. &nbsp; Shari's also has many useful tools to aid managers in controlling the amount of food used; which we will be discussing later in this class. &nbsp;&nbsp; Managers who take accurate inventories and are aware of how and when food is used usually run good food cost. &nbsp; </td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style1">&nbsp;</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td class="style3"><p align="center">Assignment </p>
    <p>In your Point Of Sale Binder (big purple binder), turn to the accounts payable chapter and read pages 6-11. &nbsp; In this reading assignment we will be studying the rules and procedures for taking inventory and learn how to use Shari's inventory program. </p></td>
